    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix global variable linkage issues causing at_error_get_format() to return incorrect values\n\n### Summary\nWhen calling at_error_get_format(), the function was returning unexpected values due to improper global variable declarations. The root cause was that global variables (at_error_format, at_error_code_suppression_q1, and at_response_format_v1) were being defined multiple times across different compilation units, leading to undefined behavior.\n\nThis manifested as the AT+CMEE? command returning incorrect error format values in some scenarios, particularly after switching between different AT command response formats using ATV0/ATV1 commands.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/API/USER/at_error.h`: Added extern declarations for global variables and included commonDef.h for bool type\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/API/USER/at_response.h`: Added extern declaration for at_response_format_v1\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/API/USER/at_command.c`: Removed duplicate extern declarations\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/API/USER/at_error.c`: Removed duplicate extern declaration and updated function documentation\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Send AT+CMEE=2 to enable verbose error reporting\n2. Send ATV0 to switch to numeric response format\n3. Send ATV1 to switch back to verbose response format\n4. Send AT+CMEE? to query the current error format\n5. Observe that the returned value may be incorrect (e.g., returning 0 instead of 2)\n\nAfter applying this fix, the AT+CMEE? command correctly returns the current error format setting that matches the last configured value.\n"
}